<subSubSection id="50B467EDFFBE2A3FFF5758A48862FAD5" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="18113466FFBE2A3FFF5758A48862FAD5" blockId="27.[151,1437,1141,1958]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFF5758A48830FB49" bold="true" box="[199,321,1249,1274]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The combination of the densely speckled forewing with some golden gloss and purple iridescence, closely juxtaposed processes of gnathos, three-lobed uncus, and unique set of cornuti in the phallus distinguishes 
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFA175943886DFAF1" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polylepiella">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFA175943886DFAF1" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">S. polylepiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other 
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFE53596C8B5DFAF1" box="[451,556,1321,1346]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFE53596C8B5DFAF1" box="[451,556,1321,1346]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species; the host-plant 
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFCA3596C8D7EFAF2" box="[819,1039,1321,1346]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Polylepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFCA3596C8D7EFAF2" box="[819,1039,1321,1346]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Polylepis racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFB8D596F8DFBFAF1" box="[1053,1162,1322,1346]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
) also makes this species distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
