<paragraph id="18113466FFBE2A3FFF575A448C42F8ED" blockId="27.[151,1437,1141,1958]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFF575A448835F9A9" bold="true" box="[199,324,1537,1562]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Bionomics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="809528E3FFBE2A3FFEC55A448887F9A9" box="[341,502,1537,1562]" captionStart="FIGURES 116 – 125" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,197,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 116 – 125. Leaf-mines of Nepticulidae species. 116 – 120, Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., host-plant Collaea speciosa (Loisel.) DC.; 119, 120, same, leaf-mines; 121 – 124, leaf-mines and cocoon of S. polylepiella Diškus &amp; Stonis, 2016 on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e); 125, leaf-mine of unknown Stigmella taxon on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556907/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Figs 121–124</figureCitation>
). Larvae mine in leaves in October. Host-plant: 
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFBB65A448CECF9AA" authority="Ruiz &amp; Pav." authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pav." box="[1062,1437,1537,1562]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Polylepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFBB65A448C74F9AA" box="[1062,1285,1537,1562]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Polylepis racemosa</emphasis>
Ruiz &amp; Pav.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFF0F5A638861F98D" box="[159,272,1574,1598]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
). Egg beige cream, mat (lustreless), oval-shaped, flattened dorso-ventrally, attached (not glued) on the leaf under side. Leaf-mine starts as a narrow gallery filled with black frass; later it develops abruptly to a large blotch with frass irregularly scattered but most of it remains accumulated in basal part of the blotch (
<figureCitation id="809528E3FFBE2A3FFABB5A288CFEF935" box="[1323,1423,1645,1670]" captionStart="FIGURES 116 – 125" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,197,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 116 – 125. Leaf-mines of Nepticulidae species. 116 – 120, Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., host-plant Collaea speciosa (Loisel.) DC.; 119, 120, same, leaf-mines; 121 – 124, leaf-mines and cocoon of S. polylepiella Diškus &amp; Stonis, 2016 on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e); 125, leaf-mine of unknown Stigmella taxon on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556907/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 121</figureCitation>
). Larva spins its cocoon inside the mine; the mine swells and becomes blisterlike at this stage (
<figureCitation id="809528E3FFBE2A3FFB5B5AD48C41F919" box="[1227,1328,1681,1706]" captionStart="FIGURES 116 – 125" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,197,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 116 – 125. Leaf-mines of Nepticulidae species. 116 – 120, Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., host-plant Collaea speciosa (Loisel.) DC.; 119, 120, same, leaf-mines; 121 – 124, leaf-mines and cocoon of S. polylepiella Diškus &amp; Stonis, 2016 on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e); 125, leaf-mine of unknown Stigmella taxon on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556907/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 124</figureCitation>
). Cocoon purplish brown to purplish dark brown; shape of the cocoon unusual, narrow; length 2.0– 
<quantity id="DF569983FFBE2A3FFB1D5AF38D97F97E" box="[1165,1254,1718,1742]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
, maximal width 
<quantity id="DF569983FFBE2A3FFF075A9F885CF942" box="[151,301,1754,1778]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.149999999999999" metricValueMax="8.299999999999999" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="0.815" valueMax="0.83" valueMin="0.8">0.8–0.83 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation id="809528E3FFBE2A3FFEAE5A9C88D3F941" box="[318,418,1753,1778]" captionStart="FIGURES 116 – 125" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,197,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 116 – 125. Leaf-mines of Nepticulidae species. 116 – 120, Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., host-plant Collaea speciosa (Loisel.) DC.; 119, 120, same, leaf-mines; 121 – 124, leaf-mines and cocoon of S. polylepiella Diškus &amp; Stonis, 2016 on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e); 125, leaf-mine of unknown Stigmella taxon on Polylepis racemosa Ruiz Lopez &amp; Pavon (after Stonis et al. 2016 e)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556907/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
). Exit slit on upper side of the leaf. Using our ‘Formula of Evaluation of Abundance and Occurrence of Leaf-miners’ (see 
<bibRefCitation id="7C3F4997FFBE2A3FFD9E5AB88B84F8A5" author="Diskus" box="[526,757,1789,1814]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refString="Diskus, A. &amp; Stonis, J. R. (2012) Leaf-mining insects of Lithuania. The Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera): taxonomy, chorological composition and trophic relationships. Monograph. Lutute Publishers, Kaunas, 220 pp. [in Lithuanian]" type="book" year="2012">Diškus, Stonis 2012</bibRefCitation>
: 52–54), 
<taxonomicName id="DFAE4FE5FFBE2A3FFCCE5AB88D25F8A5" box="[862,1108,1789,1814]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polylepiella">
<emphasis id="2ADAE874FFBE2A3FFCCE5AB88D25F8A5" box="[862,1108,1789,1814]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Stigmella polylepiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is extremely abundant in the 
<typeStatus id="C7158AC4FFBE2A3FFF075B6789B6F889" box="[151,199,1826,1850]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">type</typeStatus>
locality: a mass mining of the new species were observed (sometimes with a few leaf-mines on a single leaf); more than 300 leaf-mines with larvae were collected at a single site in Ollantaytambo, 
<collectingCountry id="60B974F6FFBE2A3FFBF25B038DE4F8EE" box="[1122,1173,1862,1885]" name="Peru" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="809528E3FFBE2A3FFB345B008C57F8ED" box="[1188,1318,1861,1886]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 18" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1922,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,208,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 18. Distribution of some central Andean Nepticulidae. 12 – 14, 17, 18, habitats, Peru; 15, 16, distribution maps." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556877/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Figs 13, 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
